about it.  It seems weird to me that someone would just suddenly start liking something out of no where.  I can't recall ever randomly deciding I was a fan of something that I had never even tried before.  It always came from some degree of exposure.  Maybe it is just one of those things, like cilantro, in the way that some people just naturally like it and some don't, but I think it's a little odd.  Does anyone else feel this way?  I mean I am glad people are liking the show and talking about it but the fact that it was literally nothing two years ago is what makes it weird to me.  People are acting like this is the best show ever but two years ago it didn't even exist.  I apologize if this is an unpopular opinion, I just had to get that off my chest.  Like I said, I am happy people are liking it, I am just surprised by how much the culture has changed in a relatively short period of time.  Also, as much as I am getting the feeling that Cowboy Bebop could be one of those rare cases of an anime that even non-anime-fans can enjoy, I will not be watching it myself.  I refuse to pay for Netflix.  They took one of my favorite shows, Arrested Development, off Amazon Prime, and made it exclusive to their service.  I am very much opposed to exclusivity deals and have no interest in supporting that business practice.  That is another thing that surprises me about Cowboy Bebop, that it is on Netflix.  I always thought it was a cult classic that only weird nerds like me knew about.  I would have guessed it to be on something like Crunchyroll.  I apologize for my ignorance.  I am sure there are plenty of people out there that are both anime fans and fans of classic American cartoons.  I have just never met any.

2. For every type definition @tparam.
  1. If @tparam is the first identifier in the type parameter list, add `<#tparam#>` to the list of open generics.
  2. If the immediately preceding generic is not `<>` but `<>, @tparam`, replace the `, @tparam` with `<#tparam#>`.

3. For every generic parameter list (not in an angle bracket context), if the first identifier in the generic parameter list is `var`, `out`, or `in`, remove it and move the rest of the generics to the right. Otherwise, remove the `<>` and move the generics to the right.

4. Go to step 1.

5. If `<>` is still part of the open generics, remove it.

6. Remove all consecutive commas at the end of a type parameter list.

7. Replace all remaining commas at the end of a type parameter list with a space.

8. If there is no space before the open angle bracket, add one.

9. If there is no space after the close angle bracket, remove it.

#### 5. Remove `generic`, `partial`, and `abstract`

Remove all three keywords.

### Conclusion

Generics in the C# type system are complex and often have to be treated differently in different contexts. This tutorial has walked the reader through a formalization of those contexts using a context-free grammar and provided a step-by-step explanation of a PEG parser that can parse C# generics. This can be used as a starting point for your own C# parser, or as inspiration for how to approach generics in other languages.

It is the largest congregational mosque in Iran after the Masjed-e Shah in Isfahan, and is one of the oldest extant structures in the city, dating from the early 11th century CE under the Buyid dynasty. It served as a model for the great Friday Mosques in Isfahan and Yazd, and is home to the shrine of the martyrdom of Jafar al-Sadiq, the sixth Shia Imam, in whose honor it is named. The mosque has undergone numerous restorations throughout its history, the most significant of which occurred in the 17th and 18th centuries CE under the Safavid and Qajar dynasties.

The main sanctuary of the mosque contains the tomb and shrine of Jafar al-Sadiq, covered with tiles and gold-plated copper. The mosque complex is enclosed by a wall, and contains four courtyards, two porticos and two minarets, one of which was restored in 1953. The mosque's main entrance faces South and contains a porch supported by twenty-two columns, most of which were added during the Timurid period. Another entrance on the West includes a grand iwan (portico), which features a monumental vaulted ceiling and is decorated with blue tiles and calligraphy. The mosque's sanctuary contains five mihrabs and three pulpits, including the pulpit of Jafar al-Sadiq himself, which is made of wood and covered with gold leaf. your home and garden, or simply give your space a refresh, there are many ways to decorate on a budget. Here are ten simple and affordable ways to decorate your home, plus tips for saving money while doing it.
1. Repurpose old furniture
Before you toss out that old dresser or table, consider giving it a new look with a fresh coat of paint or some new hardware. You can also repurpose furniture for a new use, like turning a coffee table into a ottoman or an old bookshelf into a storage bench. Get creative and give new life to your old furniture pieces.
2. Shop secondhand stores and online marketplaces
You can find some great deals on home decor at secondhand stores, flea markets, and online marketplaces like Facebook Marketplace or Craigslist. Keep an open mind and be willing to look past minor flaws or imperfections, as you can always give the piece a new coat of paint or some other customization to make it fit your style.
3. Use nature as decor
Bring the outdoors inside by using natural elements like plants, flowers, and branches as decor. You can display potted plants on shelves or window sills, or create a DIY wall hanging with dried flowers and branches. You can also use baskets or crates to create rustic storage solutions for your home.
4. Hang up inexpensive art
Art doesn't have to be expensive to make a big impact on your home decor. You can find inexpensive prints or posters online, or create your own art with canvas, paint, and a little bit of creativity. You can also display family photos or children's artwork in frames to add a personal touch to your space.
5. Update your lighting
